synthesis.justification: The three compounds were prepared under solvothermal conditions. Typically, manganese chloride tetrahydrate (cobalt chloride hexahydrate or zinc nitrate hexahydrate) and aluminum triisopropoxide were first dispersed into triglycol with stirring for 2 h, followed by the addition of imidazole. The mixture was stirred for 1 h, and the orthophosphoric acid (85 wt %) was added dropwise to give a gel with an overall molar composition of MO/Al(iPrO)3/H3PO4/imidazole/triglycol of 0.5:1.0:4.0:4.8:24.3. The gel was stirred until it was homogeneous and then was sealed in a 15-mL Teflon-lined stainless steel autoclave, and heated at 180 °C for 7 days. The final product containing large, light-pink single crystals for MnAPO-LAU (blue for CoAPO-LAU and colorless for ZnAPO-LAU) in the form of tetragonal prisms were separated by sonication, washed with distilled water, and dried in the air at room temperature.
synthesis.procedure: Disperse zinc nitrate hexahydrate and aluminum triisopropoxide into triglycol with stirring for 2 hours. Add imidazole to the mixture and stir for 1 hour. Add orthophosphoric acid (85 wt %) dropwise to form a gel with a molar composition of ZnO/Al(iPrO)3/H3PO4/imidazole/triglycol of 0.5:1.0:4.0:4.8:24.3. Stir the gel until homogeneous. Seal the gel in a 15-mL Teflon-lined stainless steel autoclave. Heat the autoclave at 180 °C for 7 days. Separate the final product containing large, colorless single crystals in the form of tetragonal prisms by sonication. Wash the crystals with distilled water and dry in the air at room temperature.

Between 100 and 150 °C, an excess metal-to-ligand ratio between 4:1 and 6:1 had to be provided.

synthesis.conditions: The synthesis was performed under an N2 atmosphere using standard glovebox or Schlenk techniques. Anhydrous, air-free DMF and methanol were deoxygenated by purging with N2 for at least 1 hour prior to use.
synthesis.justification: "Anhydrous ferrous chloride (1.1 g, 9.0 mmol), 1,4-dihydroxyterephthalic acid (0.71 g, 3.6 mmol), DMF (300 mL), and methanol (36 mL) were added to a 500 mL Schlenk flask. The reaction mixture was heated at 393 K and stirred for 18 h to afford a red-orange precipitate. The solid was collected by filtration and washed with 100 mL of DMF to yield 2.0 g (91%) of Fe2(dobdc)·4DMF." "A sample of this compound (1.9 g, 3.3 mmol) was soaked in 100 mL of DMF at 393 K for 24 h after which the solvent was decanted, and the solid was then soaked in 100 mL of methanol at 343 K for 24 h. The methanol exchange was repeated three times, and the solid was collected by filtration to yield 1.25 g (87%) of Fe2(dobdc)·4MeOH as a yellow-ochre powder." "A sample of this compound was fully desolvated by heating under dynamic vacuum (<10 μbar) at 433 K for 24 h to yield Fe2(dobdc) as a light green powder."
synthesis.procedure: Add anhydrous ferrous chloride (1.1 g, 9.0 mmol) and 1,4-dihydroxyterephthalic acid (0.71 g, 3.6 mmol) to a 500 mL Schlenk flask. Add DMF (300 mL) and methanol (36 mL) to the flask. Heat the reaction mixture at 393 K and stir for 18 hours to afford a red-orange precipitate. Collect the solid by filtration and wash with 100 mL of DMF to yield Fe2(dobdc)·4DMF. Soak a sample of this compound in 100 mL of DMF at 393 K for 24 hours, then decant the solvent. Soak the solid in 100 mL of methanol at 343 K for 24 hours, repeat the methanol exchange three times. Collect the solid by filtration to yield Fe2(dobdc)·4MeOH as a yellow-ochre powder. Fully desolvate a sample of this compound by heating under dynamic vacuum (<10 μbar) at 433 K for 24 hours to yield Fe2(dobdc) as a light green powder.
